ax + by + cz = 0 represents a plane in 3D space. Generate many points on the plane and draw them in 3D. Also indicate the direction of a vector (a,b,c) in the drawing.

The plane in 3D space

Considering the plane described as \(ax+by+cz=0\) and the vector \((a,b,c)\). Since degree of freedom on plane is 2, all we have to do is to prepare some function to return \(z\) from randomly chosen \((x,y)\) pairs.

library(rgl)
a <- sample(1:10,1)
b <- sample(1:10,1)
c <- sample(1:10,1)

n <- c(a,b,c)

x <- rnorm(100)
y <- rnorm(100)
f <- function(x,y){ -(a*x + b*y)/c }
z <- f(x,y)

f2 <- function(x){ b*x/a }
w <- f2(x)

plot3d(x,y,z,type="p")
abclines3d(0,0,0,a,b,c,add=TRUE,col=2)
planes3d(a,b,c,d=0,add=TRUE,col=3)

You must enable Javascript to view this page properly.

The vector \((a,b,c)\) is a norm vector of the plane \(ax+by+cz=0\). To confirm this, calculate the inner product between the vector parallel to the plane and \((a,b,c)\), which should be 0 regardless of the \(a,b,c\) value and the direction vector in the plane.

# For example,
a <- rnorm(1)
b <- rnorm(1)
c <- rnorm(1)
f <- function(x,y){ -(a*x + b*y)/c }

# the norm at (x1,y1,z1)
N <- 100
n <- c(a,b,c)

# the direction vector from (x1,y1,z1) on the plane
v <- matrix(rnorm(N*2),N,2)
z <- c()
for(i in 1:N){
  x <- v[i,1]
  y <- v[i,2]
  z1 <- f(x,y)
  z <- rbind(z,z1)
}
v <- cbind(v,z)

inner <- n %*% t(v)
str(inner)
##  num [1, 1:100] 0 0 0 0 0 ...
##  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
##   ..$ : NULL
##   ..$ : chr [1:100] "z1" "z1" "z1" "z1" ...
hist(inner,freq=FALSE)

The histgram, and also the each component of the matrix inner suggests that the inner product of \((a,b,c)\) and any direction vector on the plane always intersect at right angles.

Exercise 4-3

Rotate x by rotation matrix, solve the sample mean and variance-covariance matrix, and compare them with those previous. Make sure that the mean and variance are different from each other.

t <- 30
cos(t) -> ct
sin(t) -> st

Rx <- matrix(c(1,0,0,0,ct,-st,0,st,ct),3,3)
Ry <- matrix(c(ct,0,st,0,1,0,-st,0,ct),3,3)
Rz <- matrix(c(ct,-st,0,st,ct,0,0,0,1),3,3)

x2 <- t(Rx %*% Ry %*% Rz %*% t(x))

m2 <- c(mean(x2[,1]),mean(x2[,2]),mean(x2[,3]))

Make sure that the sum of the variance does not change though the values of variance are different. Calculate trace of variance-covariance matrices, and also regard the trace as the sum of the eigen values of variance-covariance matrices.

tr <- sum(diag(var))
tr
## [1] 333.3476
tr2 <- sum(diag(var2))
tr2

esum <- sum(eigen(var)$value)

Exercise 4-5

The sum of the variance of each axis does not change depending on the x axis transformed by rotation, but the distribution of the sum of variance is different. Make sure the fact by the following steps; 1. create a number of random rotation matrices 2. rotate datasets using the matrices 3. calculate the variance along each axis 4. plot the variance in ascending order 5. confirm the change of the distribution.

R <- function(t){
  cos(t) -> ct
  sin(t) -> st
  Rx <- matrix(c(1,0,0,0,ct,-st,0,st,ct),3,3)
  Ry <- matrix(c(ct,0,st,0,1,0,-st,0,ct),3,3)
  Rz <- matrix(c(ct,-st,0,st,ct,0,0,0,1),3,3)
  R <- Rx %*% Ry %*% Rz
}

for(i in 1:100){
  t <- rnorm(1)
  xr <- t( R(t) %*% t(x) )
  ev <- diag(var(xr))
  var <- c(min(ev),median(ev),max(ev))
  order <- c(1,2,3)
  plot(order,var,xlab="order",ylab="var",type="l",col=i, lty=4)
  par(new=T)
}

Plot the variance of each axis obtained by rotation which diagonize variance-covariance matrix.

R <- function(t){
  cos(t) -> ct
  sin(t) -> st
  Rx <- matrix(c(1,0,0,0,ct,-st,0,st,ct),3,3)
  Ry <- matrix(c(ct,0,st,0,1,0,-st,0,ct),3,3)
  Rz <- matrix(c(ct,-st,0,st,ct,0,0,0,1),3,3)
  R <- Rx %*% Ry %*% Rz
}

for(i in 1:100){
  t <- rnorm(1)
  xr <- t( R(t) %*% t(x) )
  ev <- diag(var(xr))
  var <- c(min(ev),median(ev),max(ev))
  order <- c(1,2,3)
  plot(order,var,xlab="order",ylab="var",type="l",col=1, lty=4)
  par(new=T)
}
var.e <- diag(eigen(var(x))$value)
vare <- c(min(var.e),median(var.e),max(var.e))

plot(vare,type="l",col=2)

Increase the number of variables.

d <- 10
n <- 1000
X <- matrix(rnorm(d*n),ncol=d)
X <- apply(X,2,cumsum)

plot(as.data.frame(X[,1:5],pch=20,cex=0.1))

Var.e <- diag(eigen(var(X))$value)
chnum <- choose(n=10,k=3)
comb <- combn(x=diag(Var.e),m=3)

for(i in 1:chnum){
  Vare <- c(min(comb[,i]),median(comb[,i]),max(comb[,i]))
  order <- c(1,2,3)
  plot(order,Vare,xlab="order",ylab="var",type="l",col=i, lty=4)
  par(new=T)
}

Var.e <- diag(eigen(var(X))$value)
chnum <- choose(n=10,k=3)
comb <- combn(x=diag(Var.e),m=3)

for(i in 1:chnum){
  Vare <- c(min(comb[,i]),median(comb[,i]),max(comb[,i]))
  order <- c(1,2,3)
  plot(order,Vare,xlab="order",ylab="var",type="l",col=1, lty=4)
  par(new=T)
}
